    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Let's dive into the technical aspects. When a beam is subjected to a bending moment, the concrete's compressive strength is indeed sufficient to resist the compressive forces. However, the tensile stresses that develop in the concrete due to the bending moment can cause cracking.\n\nThe steel rebar helps to redistribute these tensile stresses by providing a path for the concrete to deform in a more controlled manner. When a bending moment is applied to a beam, the concrete on the side of the beam that's being compressed (the \"top\" side) will experience tensile stresses due to Poisson's ratio, which causes the concrete to contract laterally.\n\nThe steel rebar, on the other hand, is able to resist these tensile stresses by providing a tensile reinforcement. The rebar acts as a \"tensile anchor\" that helps to transfer the tensile forces from the concrete to the rebar, allowing the concrete to deform in a more controlled manner.\n\nIn terms of the actual physics, the steel rebar is typically spaced at a distance of about 12-18 inches (300-450 mm) on center, which is known as the \"rebar spacing.\" When a bending moment is applied to the beam, the rebar",
